            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Svetlana Abramov\u2019s life is a study in contrasts, a journey from the rigid atheism of the Soviet Union to the holistic healing arts of San Francisco. Born in Leningrad in 1973, her childhood was defined by concrete apartment blocks, long winters, and a state-mandated belief in scientific materialism. Her father was an engineer, her mother a factory administrator\u2014practical people who viewed the world through a lens of unyielding logic.\n\nThe first crack in this worldview appeared in her late teens. Her mother developed a debilitating chronic pain condition that stoic Soviet doctors dismissed with inadequate painkillers. Watching her mother suffer, Svetlana felt a growing disillusionment with the limitations of the medicine she knew. When the Soviet Union collapsed, a future she never imagined possible opened up. At 22, armed with a small inheritance and a fierce desire for something more, she immigrated to San Francisco, drawn by its reputation for openness and change.\n\nHer first years were a struggle of dishwashing jobs and English classes. A turning point came when a stress-induced migraine led her, on a friend\u2019s desperate recommendation, into a small, fragrant acupuncture clinic in Chinatown. The relief was immediate and profound, but the real revelation was the philosophy behind it\u2014a system that saw the body not as a machine to be fixed, but as an ecosystem to be balanced. It was the answer to a question she didn't even know she was asking.\n\nWith newfound purpose, Svetlana enrolled in a graduate program for Traditional Chinese Medicine. It was an arduous but soul-affirming path. She opened her own practice, \u201cInner Balance Acupuncture,\u201d a decade ago in the Inner Richmond. Her life is now a deliberate-yet-gentle routine. She lives just a half-mile from her clinic, a walk she treasures for its quiet transition between home and work. Her days are filled with the scent of moxa and herbal decoctions, and the quiet trust of her clients, who have become her chosen family.\n\nNow 51 and comfortably single, Svetlana has built the stability she once lacked. Her dream is not for wealth or expansion, but for depth: to continue her studies, perhaps travel to China to see the origins of her practice, and to remain a grounding, healing presence in the community she has so lovingly adopted as her own."
        },
